  "prompt": "Why isn't desalination the answer to India's water scarcity problem?",
  "response": "Desalination faces several challenges in addressing India's water scarcity:\n\n1. High Cost\n- Expensive infrastructure and technology\n- High energy consumption makes process costly\n- Operating expenses are significantly higher than traditional water sources\n\n2. Energy Requirements\n- Significant electricity needed for reverse osmosis process\n- India's electricity grid is already strained\n- High carbon footprint compared to other water sources\n\n3. Environmental Concerns\n- Discharge of concentrated salt brine damages marine ecosystems\n- Potential negative impact on coastal environments\n- High water intake can harm marine life\n\n4. Geographic Limitations\n- Most water-scarce regions are inland\n- Coastal desalination plants benefit only limited areas\n- Transportation of desalinated water inland is complex and expensive\n\n5. Maintenance Challenges\n- Complex technology requiring specialized technical expertise\n- High maintenance costs\n- Risk of equipment failure\n\n6. Alternative Options\n- Cheaper water management strategies available\n- Rainwater harvesting\n- Water conservation\n- Improved irrigation techniques\n- Groundwater management\n\nWhile desalination is part of potential water solutions, it's not a comprehensive answer to India's water scarcity due to these significant practical and economic limitations.",
